    33тЖТ/// A value in a key-value.
    34тЖТ///
    35тЖТ/// Values are an anonymous bag containing some structured datum.
    36тЖТ///
    37тЖТ/// # Capturing values
    38тЖТ///
    39тЖТ/// There are a few ways to capture a value:
    40тЖТ///
    41тЖТ/// - Using the `Value::from_*` methods.
    42тЖТ/// - Using the `ToValue` trait.
    43тЖТ/// - Using the standard `From` trait.
    44тЖТ///
    45тЖТ/// ## Using the `Value::from_*` methods
    46тЖТ///
    47тЖТ/// `Value` offers a few constructor methods that capture values of different kinds.
    48тЖТ///
    49тЖТ/// ```
    50тЖТ/// use log::kv::Value;
    51тЖТ///
    52тЖТ/// let value = Value::from_debug(&42i32);
    53тЖТ///
    54тЖТ/// assert_eq!(None, value.to_i64());
    55тЖТ/// ```
    56тЖТ///
    57тЖТ/// ## Using the `ToValue` trait
    58тЖТ///
    59тЖТ/// The `ToValue` trait can be used to capture values generically.
    60тЖТ/// It's the bound used by `Source`.
    61тЖТ///
    62тЖТ/// ```
    63тЖТ/// # use log::kv::ToValue;
    64тЖТ/// let value = 42i32.to_value();
    65тЖТ///
    66тЖТ/// assert_eq!(Some(42), value.to_i64());
    67тЖТ/// ```
    68тЖТ///
    69тЖТ/// ## Using the standard `From` trait
    70тЖТ///
    71тЖТ/// Standard types that implement `ToValue` also implement `From`.
    72тЖТ///
    73тЖТ/// ```
    74тЖТ/// use log::kv::Value;
    75тЖТ///
    76тЖТ/// let value = Value::from(42i32);
    77тЖТ///
    78тЖТ/// assert_eq!(Some(42), value.to_i64());
    79тЖТ/// ```
    80тЖТ///
    81тЖТ/// # Data model
    82тЖТ///
    83тЖТ/// Values can hold one of a number of types:
    84тЖТ///
    85тЖТ/// - **Null:** The absence of any other meaningful value. Note that
    86тЖТ///   `Some(Value::null())` is not the same as `None`. The former is
    87тЖТ///   `null` while the latter is `undefined`. This is important to be
    88тЖТ///   able to tell the difference between a key-value that was logged,
    89тЖТ///   but its value was empty (`Some(Value::null())`) and a key-value
    90тЖТ///   that was never logged at all (`None`).
    91тЖТ/// - **Strings:** `str`, `char`.
    92тЖТ/// - **Booleans:** `bool`.
    93тЖТ/// - **Integers:** `u8`-`u128`, `i8`-`i128`, `NonZero*`.
    94тЖТ/// - **Floating point numbers:** `f32`-`f64`.
    95тЖТ/// - **Errors:** `dyn (Error + 'static)`.
    96тЖТ/// - **`serde`:** Any type in `serde`'s data model.
    97тЖТ/// - **`sval`:** Any type in `sval`'s data model.
    98тЖТ///
    99тЖТ/// # Serialization
   100тЖТ///
   101тЖТ/// Values provide a number of ways to be serialized.
   102тЖТ///
   103тЖТ/// For basic types the [`Value::visit`] method can be used to extract the
   104тЖТ/// underlying typed value. However, this is limited in the amount of types
   105тЖТ/// supported (see the [`VisitValue`] trait methods).
   106тЖТ///
   107тЖТ/// For more complex types one of the following traits can be used:
   108тЖТ///  * `sval::Value`, requires the `kv_sval` feature.
   109тЖТ///  * `serde::Serialize`, requires the `kv_serde` feature.
   110тЖТ///
   111тЖТ/// You don't need a visitor to serialize values through `serde` or `sval`.
   112тЖТ///
   113тЖТ/// A value can always be serialized using any supported framework, regardless
   114тЖТ/// of how it was captured. If, for example, a value was captured using its
   115тЖТ/// `Display` implementation, it will serialize through `serde` as a string. If it was
   116тЖТ/// captured as a struct using `serde`, it will also serialize as a struct
   117тЖТ/// through `sval`, or can be formatted using a `Debug`-compatible representation.
   118тЖТ#[derive(Clone)]
   119тЖТpub struct Value<'v> {
